<DATE>pkgsrc-sig 25 Sep 2001 - Digital signatures for binary packages
    Alistair Crooks has committed changes to pkg_add(1); adding the
    ability to verify the contents of a binary package by using
    digital signatures.  This has been accomplished by added a
    "<tt>-s <i>verification-type</i></tt>" command line
    argument to pkg_add(1).
    <p>
    The following verification types have been defined:
    <tt>gpg</tt> (pkgsrc/security/<PKGSRC>security/gnupg),
    <tt>pgp5</tt> (pkgsrc/security/<PKGSRC>security/pgp5),
    and <tt>none</tt>.  Callouts are made to the relevant
    programs to verify the contents of the binary package, and
    its provenance. You are then asked whether you want to
    proceed with the installation. The "<tt>none</tt>" verification
    type is the same as the existing behaviour, and is also the
    default - in which case, no verification of the binary package
    is done.
    <p>
    The verification type is passed onto recursive pkg_add(1)
    invocations for dependent packages
    <p>
    At the moment, the ability to verify packages is limited to
    those which are not specified by URL; removing this restriction
    is being looked at.
    <p>
    More details are located in Alistair's announcement in the <a
    href="http://mail-index.NetBSD.org/tech-pkg/2001/09/25/0005.html">tech-pkg
    mail archive</a>.

