<DATE>sa-010725 25 Jul 2001 - Four new Security Advisories released
    <p>
    NetBSD Security Advisories <a
    href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-009.txt.asc">SA2001-009</a>, <a
    href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-010.txt.asc">SA2001-010</a>, <a
    href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-011.txt.asc">SA2001-011</a>, and <a
    href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-012.txt.asc">SA2001-012</a>
    have been released.  More details,
    including information on solutions and workarounds, are located
    in each individual security advisory.
    <p>
    The fixes for SA2001-009, SA2001-010, and SA2001-011 are all present
    in NetBSD 1.5.1.  SA2001-012 affects releases up to and including
    NetBSD 1.5.1.
    <p>
    <ul>
     <li><b><a href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-009.txt.asc">NetBSD
       Security Advisory SA2001-009</a></b> -
       Race condition between sugid-exec and ptrace(2).
       A race condition  can allow a local user to cause a setuid-root
       executable to execute arbitrary code as the superuser.
       <p>
<pre>Fixed: NetBSD-current:    June 15, 2001
       NetBSD-1.5 branch: June 17, 2001 (1.5.1 includes the fix)
       NetBSD-1.4 branch: July 19, 2001</pre>
       <p>
     <li><b><a href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-010.txt.asc">NetBSD
       Security Advisory SA2001-010</a></b> -
       sshd(8) "cookies" file mishandling on X11 forwarding.
       Rogue local users can abuse this to remove any file named
       "cookies" using root privileges if X11 forwarding is enabled.
       <p>
<pre>Fixed: NetBSD-current:    June 14, 2001
       NetBSD-1.5 branch: June 25, 2001 (1.5.1 includes the fix)
       pkgsrc openssh:    openssh-2.9p2 corrects this issue</pre>
       <p>
     <li><b><a href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-011.txt.asc">NetBSD
       Security Advisory SA2001-011</a></b> -
       Insufficient msg_controllen checking for sendmsg(2).
       Due to insufficient length checking in the kernel, sendmsg(2) can
       be used by a local user to cause a kernel trap, or an 'out of
       space in kmem_map' panic.
       <p>
<pre>Fixed: NetBSD-current:    July 1, 2001
       NetBSD-1.5 branch: July 2, 2001 (1.5.1 includes the fix)
       NetBSD-1.4 branch: July 19, 2001</pre>
       <p>
     <li><b><a href="ftp://ftp.NetBSD.org/pub/NetBSD/security/advisories/NetBSD-SA2001-012.txt.asc">NetBSD
       Security Advisory SA2001-012</a></b> -
       telnetd(8) options overflow.
       A buffer overflow existed in the telnetd(8) program. Any client
       connecting could cause the telnetd instance to SEGV, and possibly
       to execute arbitrary code as root
       <p>
<pre>Fixed: NetBSD-current:    July 19, 2001
       NetBSD-1.5 branch: Use supplied patch
       NetBSD-1.4 branch: Use supplied patch</pre>
    </ul>
    <p>
    More information on previous <a
    href="../Security/advisory.html">Security Advisories</a> is
    available in the <a href="../Security/">NetBSD Security</a> pages.

